{{Use British English|date=May 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}} {{Italic title}} {{Infobox event | title = ''Pink Floyd: Their Mortal Remains'' | image = Pink Floyd Their Mortal Remains - 2017-10-13 - Andy Mabbett - 11.jpg | image_size = | image_upright = | image_alt = | caption = Pink Floyd's 1975-1977 "Rotating flower-petal [[Disco ball|mirror ball]]" at the V&A | date = {{start date|2017|05|13|df=y}} - present | type = Museum exhibition | theme = [[Pink Floyd]] | awards = | website = {{URL|vam.ac.uk/exhibitions/pink-floyd}} }}
'''''Pink Floyd: Their Mortal Remains''''' is an exhibition on the history of the British rock band [[Pink Floyd]], opening on 13 May 2017 (with a museum members' preview on 12 May) at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] in London, England, and originally scheduled to run until 1 October.<ref name="BBC-39869029">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39869029|title=Sneak peak inside new Pink Floyd exhibition|date=10 May 2017|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref><ref name="Petridis">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/may/09/pink-floyd-exhibition-their-mortal-remains-review-v-and-a |title=The Pink Floyd Exhibition: Their Mortal Remains review – look, a flying pig!|last=Petridis|first=Alexis |authorlink=Alexis Petridis |date=9 May 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref><ref name="Aspden">{{cite web |url=https://www.ft.com/content/18fcfde0-33d1-11e7-99bd-13beb0903fa3 |title=Pink Floyd at the V&A: the lovely sound of anomie in the UK |last=Aspden |first=Peter |date=8 May 2017 |work=[[Financial Times]] |accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref><ref name="Zemler">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/inside-pink-floyds-immersive-new-museum-exhibit-w481676|title=Inside Pink Floyd's Immersive New Museum Exhibit|last=Zemler|first=Emily|date=11 May 2017|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref><ref name="Bonner">{{cite web |url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/blog/pink-floyd-mortal-remains-reviewed-100254 |title=Pink Floyd: Their Mortal Remains reviewed |last=Bonner |first=Michael|date=9 May 2017|work=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref><ref name="Dunton">{{cite web|url=http://www.smash.com/pink-floyd-their-mortal-remains/|title=Pink Floyd Exhibition: Their Mortal Remains Exhibition Review|last=Dunton|first=Wesley|date=11 May 2017|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref><ref name="CW">{{cite web |url=https://www.culturewhisper.com/r/visual_arts/victoria_and_albert_pink_floyd_show_london/7560 |title=Review: Pink Floyd, V&A ★★★★★ |work=Culture Whisper |accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref> After high visitor numbers, the exhibition's run was extended by two weeks, to 15 October 2017.<ref name="Dex">{{cite news|last1=Dex|first1=Robert|title=V&A's smash hit Pink Floyd exhibition to run for extra two weeks|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/arts/vas-pink-floyd-exhibition-to-run-for-an-extra-fortnight-after-record-visit-numbers-a3622836.html|accessdate=14 October 2017|work=Evening Standard|date=30 August 2017}}</ref> It followed the V&As successful ''[[David Bowie Is]]'' exhibition.<ref name="Bonner" />
[[File:Pink Floyd Their Mortal Remains - 2017-10-13 - Andy Mabbett - 60.jpg|thumb|Head of the 'wife' puppet from the original [[The Wall Tour (1980–81)|The Wall concerts]]]]
The exhibition's title reflects the lyric "I've got a grand piano to prop up my mortal remains", from the song "[[Nobody Home]]", on ''[[The Wall (Pink Floyd)|The Wall]]''. It was promoted with media appearances by all three surviving band members ([[David Gilmour]], [[Nick Mason]] and [[Roger Waters]]), and designer [[Aubrey Powell (designer)|Aubrey Powell]];<ref name="Dunton" /> as well as the flying of an [[Pink Floyd pigs|inflatable pig]] over the V&A,<ref name="Bonner" /> and at the BBC's [[Broadcasting House]].<ref name="Telegraph-pig">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/11/pictures-day-11-may-2017/pink-floyd-inflatable-pig-floats-next-broadcasting-house-promote/|title=The Pink Floyd inflatable pig floats next to Broadcasting House to promote their new exhibition at the V&A museum - Pictures of the Day|date=11 May 2017|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref>
Treating the band's history in chronological order, the exhibition ends with their 2005 reunion at [[Live 8]],<ref name="Aspden" /> with footage of the band performing "[[Comfortably Numb]]", using specially-remixed audio, delivered via [[AMBEO]], a [[Sennheiser]] 3D audio technology, over 17 channels and 25 speakers, seven of which are [[subwoofer]]s.<ref name="Dunton" /><ref name="Zemler" />
[[File:Pink Floyd Their Mortal Remains - 2017-10-13 - Andy Mabbett - 54 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Mask cast from [[Richard Wright (musician)|Richard Wright]]'s face and worn by a member of the "surrogate band" during '[[In the Flesh?]]', the opening number of [[The Wall Tour (1980–81)|The Wall concerts]], in order to fool audiences into thinking they were Wright.]]
Objects shown include documents such as a page from Nick Mason’s diary for 1968 and a 1975 tour rider, a "flower petal" shaped [[Disco ball|mirrorball]] used from 1973 to 1975, instruments, plus equipment including the [[Azimuth Co-ordinator]] and the band's [[Binson Echorec|Binson Echorec Baby]] effects unit.<ref name="Petridis" /><ref name="Bonner" /> There are several props from the 1980 and 1981 [[The Wall Tour (1980–81)|''The Wall'' concerts]], including the face masks worn by members of the 'surrogate band', to make them look like Pink Floyd.<ref name="Bonner" /><ref name="Petridis" /><ref>{{Cite book |publisher = Omnibus press |isbn=978-1-84938-370-7 |last= Mabbett |first=Andy| title=Pink Floyd - The Music and the Mystery |year=2010}}</ref> Also on show are a hand-written letter from [[Syd Barrett]] to Jenny Spires, his then girlfriend; and his bicycle.<ref name="Bonner" />
The organisers plan to tour the exhibition internationally, for up to ten years.<ref name="Zemler" /> In November 2017, it was announced that the next venue would be [[Rome]], Italy, opening on 19 January 2018.<ref name="Sennheiser - Rome">{{cite web|title=Sennheiser - Headphones & Headsets - Microphones - Integrated Systems|url=https://en-uk.sennheiser.com/news-pink-floyd-announce-rome-as-the-second-city-for-the-pink-floyd-exhibition-their-mortal-remains|publisher=Sennheiser|accessdate=30 November 2017|language=en}}</ref>
