{{Party politics}}
'''Third Position''' is an [[ideology]] that was developed in the late 20th century by [[political parties]] including [[Terza Posizione]] in Italy and [[Third Way (France)|Troisième Voie]] in France. It emphasizes opposition to both [[communism]] and [[capitalism]]. Advocates of Third Position politics typically present themselves as "beyond left and right" while [[syncretic politics|syncretizing]] ideas from each end of the [[political spectrum]], usually [[reactionary]] [[Cultural conservatism|right-wing cultural]] views and [[political radicalism|radical]] [[Left-wing politics#Economics|left-wing economic]] views.<ref name="Berlet 1990-1999">{{cite journal | author = [[Chip Berlet|Berlet, Chip]] | title = Right Woos Left: Populist Party, LaRouchite, and Other Neo-fascist Overtures To Progressives, And Why They Must Be Rejected | date = 20 December 1990 |quote= revised 4/15/1994, 3 corrections 1999 | url = http://www.publiceye.org/rightwoo/rwooz9_TOC.html |publisher= Political Research Associates| accessdate = 2010-02-01}}</ref><ref name="Griffin 1995">{{cite book | author = [[Roger Griffin|Griffin, Roger]] | title = [[Fascism (book)|Fascism]] | publisher = Oxford University Press | year = 1995 | isbn = 0-19-289249-5}}</ref><ref name="Coogan 1999">{{cite book| author = Kevin Coogan | title = Dreamer of the Day: Francis Parker Yockey and the Postwar Fascist International | publisher = Autonomedia | year = 1999 | isbn = 1-57027-039-2}}</ref><ref name="Lee 1999">{{cite book| author = [[Martin A. Lee|Lee, Martin A.]] | title = The Beast Reawakens: Fascism's Resurgence from Hitler's Spymasters to Today's Neo-Nazi Groups and Right-Wing Extremists | publisher = Routledge | year = 1999 | isbn = 0-415-92546-0}}</ref><ref name="Griffin 2000">{{cite journal | author = [[Roger Griffin|Griffin, Roger]] | title = Interregnum or Endgame? Radical Right Thought in the 'Post-fascist' Era |journal=[[Journal of Political Ideologies]] |volume= 5 | issue = 2 | pages= 163–78 | date = July 2000 | url = https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=gmail&attid=0.1&thid=12d29dce1f372f76&mt=application/msword&url=https://mail.google.com/mail/?ui%3D2%26ik%3Dd0b3911faa%26view%3Datt%26th%3D12d29dce1f372f76%26attid%3D0.1%26disp%3Dattd%26realattid%3Df_gi7wyv840%26zw&sig=AHIEtbT-PMWGypv4250ujXxj4NPID8uFxg&pli=1 | accessdate = 2010-12-27 | doi= 10.1080/713682938}}</ref><ref name="Antonio 2000">{{cite journal | author = Antonio, Robert J. | title = After Postmodernism: Reactionary Tribalism | journal = American Journal of Sociology | volume = 106 | number = 1 | pages = 40–87 | year = 2000 | jstor = 3081280 | doi=10.1086/303111}}</ref><ref name="Sunshine 2008">{{cite journal | author = Sunshine, Spencer | title = Rebranding Fascism: National-Anarchists | date = Winter 2008 | url = http://www.publiceye.org/magazine/v23n4/rebranding_fascism.html | accessdate = 2009-11-12}}</ref>

==History==
{{unreferenced section|date=June 2018}}
The term "Third Position" was coined in Europe and the main precursors of Third Position politics were [[National Bolshevism]] (a synthesis of far-right ultranationalism and far-left [[Bolsheviks|Bolshevik]] socialism) and [[Strasserism]] (a radical, mass-action, worker-based, socialist form of [[National Socialism]], advocated by the "left-wing" of the [[Nazi Party]] until it was crushed in the [[Night of the Long Knives]] in 1934 ). [[Neo-fascist]], [[Neo-Nazi]] author [[Francis Parker Yockey]] had proposed an alliance between [[Communism|communists]] and fascists called ''Red-Brown Alliance'' (Red being the color of communism and Brown being the color of Nazism) which would have been anti-Semitic, anti-American, and anti-Zionist in nature. Yockey lent support to [[Third World]] liberation movements as well.

==Argentina==
At the peak of the [[Cold War]], the former [[Argentine]] [[President of Argentina|President]] [[Juan Perón]] (1946–1955; 1973–1974) defined the international position of his doctrine ([[Peronism]]) as a Third Position between capitalism and communism, a stance which became a precedent of the [[Non-Aligned Movement]]. {{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} 

{{quote|Until we proclaimed our doctrine, in front of us, capitalist individualism and communist collectivism rose triumphal, the shadow of their imperial wings extending in every path open to mankind… This way, Justicialism was born, under the supreme aspiration of a high ideal. The Justicialism, created by us and for our descendants, as a third ideological position aimed to liberate us from capitalism without making us fall into the oppressing claws of collectivism.| Juan Domingo Peron addressing the Congress in 1952.<ref>http://archivohistorico.educ.ar/sites/default/files/VI_53.pdf</ref>}}

==England==
{{main|International Third Position}}
{{stub section|date=October 2017}}
International Third Position (ITP) was a [[neo-fascist]] organisation formed by the breakaway faction of the [[British National Front]],<ref name="WTO">{{cite book|author1=Patrick F. J. Macrory |author2=Arthur Edmond Appleton |author3=Michael G. Plummer |title=The World Trade Organization: Legal, Economic and Political Analysis|publisher=Springer|year=2005|pages=467|isbn=0-387-22685-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=96x7IwWDJUQC&pg=RA1-PT2944&dq=%22International+Third+Position%22+neo-fascist}}</ref> led by [[Roberto Fiore]], an ex-member of the Italian far-right movement [[Terza Posizione|Third Position]].<ref name="Ryan">{{cite book|last= Ryan|first=Nick|title=Into a World of Hate: A Journey Among the Extreme Right|publisher=Routledge|year=2004|pages=62|isbn=0-415-94922-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wOq79eHTJu4C&pg=PA62&dq=%22International+Third+Position%22+neo-fascist}}</ref>

==France==
{{main|Third Way (France)}}
{{unreferenced section|date=June 2018}}
During the 1930s and 1940s, a number of splinter groups from the [[Far-left politics|radical left]] became associated with [[radical nationalism]]. [[Jacques Doriot]]'s [[French Popular Party]] (from the [[French Communist Party]]) and [[Marcel Déat]]'s [[National Popular Rally]] (from the [[French Section of the Workers' International]]). Third Position ideology gained some support in [[France]], where in 1985 [[Jean-Gilles Malliarakis]] set up a "Third Way" political party, [[Third Way (France)|Troisième Voie]] (TV). Considering its main enemies to be the [[United States]], [[communism]] and [[Zionism]], the group advocated radical paths to national revolution. Associated for a time with the [[Groupe Union Défense]], TV was generally on poor terms with [[National Front (France)|Front National]] until 1991, when Malliarakis decided to approach them. As a result, TV fell apart and a radical splinter group under [[Christian Bouchet]], [[Nouvelle Résistance]], adopted National Bolshevik and then [[Eurasianism|Eurasianist]] views.

==Italy==
{{main|Terza Posizione}}
{{unreferenced section|date=June 2018}}
In [[Italy]], the Third Position was developed by [[Roberto Fiore]], along with [[Gabriele Adinolfi]] and [[Giuseppe Dimitri|Peppe Dimitri]], in the tradition of Italian [[neo-fascism]]. Third Position’s ideology is characterized by a [[militarism|militarist]] formulation, a [[palingenetic ultranationalism]] looking favourably to national [[Liberation movement|liberation movements]], support for [[Racism|racial separatism]] and the adherence to a [[Political Soldier|soldier lifestyle]]. In order to construct a cultural background for the ideology, Fiore looked to the [[ruralism]] of [[Julius Evola]] and sought to combine it with the desire for a cultural-spiritual revolution. He adopted some of the positions of the contemporary [[Far-right politics|far-right]], notably the [[ethnopluralism]] of [[Alain de Benoist]] and the [[Europe]]-wide appeal associated with such views as the [[Europe a Nation]] campaign of [[Oswald Mosley]] (amongst others). Fiore was one of the founders of the [[Terza Posizione]] movement in 1978. Third Position ideas are now represented in Italy by [[Forza Nuova]], led by Fiore; and by the movement [[CasaPound]], a network of [[far-right social centres]].

==United States==
In the [[United States]], the [[Political Research Associates]] argue that Third Position politics has been promoted by some [[white nationalism|white nationalist]] and [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]] groups such as the [[National Alliance (United States)|National Alliance]], [[American Front]], [[Traditionalist Worker Party]] and [[White Aryan Resistance]] as well as some [[black nationalism|black nationalist]] groups such as the [[Nation of Islam]], since the late 20th century.<ref name="Berlet 1990-1999"/> In 2010, the American Third Position Party (later renamed [[American Freedom Party]]) was founded in part to channel the [[right-wing populism|right-wing populist]] resentment engendered by the [[financial crisis of 2007–2010]] and the policies of the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]].<ref name="SPLC 2010">{{cite journal| author = [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] | title = Prof Has New Job Running Racist Political Party: Academic Anti-Semitism | date = Spring 2010 | url = http://www.splcenter.org/get-informed/intelligence-report/browse-all-issues/2010/spring/psych-prof-has-new-job-running-racist | accessdate = 2010-04-28}}</ref>

